# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] In computer programming, the **async/await pattern** is a syntactic feature of many programming languages that allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] The feature is found in C#, C++, Python, F#, Hack, Julia, Dart, Kotlin, Rust, Nim, JavaScript, and Swift.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] F# added asynchronous workflows with await points in version 2.0 in 2007.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] This influenced the async/await mechanism added to C#.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Haskell lead developer Simon Marlow created the async package in 2010.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Microsoft first released a version of C# with async/await in the Async CTP (2011).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] It was later officially released in C# 5 (2012).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Python added support for async/await with version 3.5 in 2015 adding 2 new keywords, `async` and `await`.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] TypeScript added support for async/await with version 1.7 in 2015.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] JavaScript added support for async/await in 2017 as part of ECMAScript 2017 JavaScript edition.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Rust added support for async/await with version 1.39.0 in 2019 using the `async` keyword and the `.await` postfix operator, both introduced in the 2018 edition of the language.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] C++ added support for async/await with version 20 in 2020 with 3 new keywords `co_return`, `co_await`, `co_yield`.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Swift added support for async/await with version 5.5 in 2021, adding 2 new keywords `async` and `await`.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] This was released alongside a concrete implementation of the Actor model with the `actor` keyword which uses async/await to mediate access to each actor from outside.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] A function using async/await can use as many `await` expressions as it wants, and each will be handled in the same way (though a promise will only be returned to the caller for the first await, while every other await will utilize internal callbacks).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] A function can also hold a promise object directly and do other processing first (including starting other asynchronous tasks), delaying awaiting the promise until its result is needed.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Functions with promises also have promise aggregation methods that allow the program to await multiple promises at once or in some special pattern (such as C#'s `Task.WhenAll()`, which returns a valueless `Task` that resolves when all of the tasks in the arguments have resolved).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Many promise types also have additional features beyond what the async/await pattern normally uses, such as being able to set up more than one result callback or inspect the progress of an especially long-running task.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] In the particular case of C#, and in many other languages with this language feature, the async/await pattern is not a core part of the language's runtime, but is instead implemented with lambdas or continuations at compile time.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Because of this, if an interface method needs to return a promise object, but itself does not require `await` in the body to wait on any asynchronous tasks, it does not need the `async` modifier either and can instead return a promise object directly.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] For instance, a function might be able to provide a promise that immediately resolves to some result value (such as C#'s `Task.FromResult()`), or it may simply return another method's promise that happens to be the exact promise needed (such as when deferring to an overload).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] One important caveat of this functionality, however, is that while the code resembles traditional blocking code, the code is actually non-blocking and potentially multithreaded, meaning that many intervening events may occur while waiting for the promise targeted by an `await` to resolve.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] The C language does not support await/async.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Some coroutine libraries such as *s_task* simulate the keywords await/async with macros.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] In C++, await (named `co_await` in C++ to emphasise its context in coroutines) has been officially merged into C++20.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Support for it, coroutines, and the keywords such as `co_await` are available in GCC and MSVC compilers while Clang has partial support.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] To call it, use `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] It is worth noting that `std::promise` and `std::future`, although it would seem that they would be awaitable objects, implement none of the machinery required to be returned from coroutines and be awaited using `co_await`.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Programmers must implement a number of public member functions, such as `await_ready`, `await_suspend`, and `await_resume` on the return type in order for the type to be awaited on.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] In 2012, C# added the async/await pattern in C# with version 5.0, which Microsoft refers to as the task-based asynchronous pattern (TAP).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Async methods usually return either `void`, `Task`, `Task<T>`, `ValueTask` or `ValueTask<T>`.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] User code can define custom types that async methods can return through custom *async method builders* but this is an advanced and rare scenario.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Async methods that return `void` are intended for event handlers; in most cases where a synchronous method would return `void`, returning `Task` instead is recommended, as it allows for more intuitive exception handling (note that `Task<void>` is invalid in C#).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Methods that make use of `await` must be declared with the `async` keyword.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] In methods that have a return value of type `Task<T>`, methods declared with `async` must have a return statement of type assignable to `T` instead of `Task<T>`; the compiler wraps the value in the `Task<T>` generic.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] It is also possible to `await` methods that have a return type of `Task` or `Task<T>` that are declared without `async`.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] The following async method downloads data from a URL using `await`.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Because this method issues a task for each URI before requiring completion with the `await` keyword, the resources can load at the same time instead of waiting for the last resource to finish before starting to load the next.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] In 2007, F# added asynchronous workflows with version 2.0.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] The asynchronous workflows are implemented as CE (computation expressions).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] They can be defined without specifying any special context (like `async` in C#).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] F# asynchronous workflows append a bang (!) to keywords to start asynchronous tasks.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Java does not have `async` and `await` keywords in the language, however it can be emulated using the `java.util.concurrent` package, such as the class `CompletableFuture` (introduced in Java 8).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Asynchronous programming is later improved in Java 21 with the introduction of virtual threads and structured task scopes.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] The await operator in JavaScript (and TypeScript) can only be used from inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] If the parameter is a promise, execution of the async function will resume when the promise is resolved (unless the promise is rejected, in which case an error will be thrown that can be handled with normal JavaScript exception handling).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] If the parameter is not a promise, the parameter itself will be returned immediately.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Many libraries provide promise objects that can also be used with await, as long as they match the specification for native JavaScript promises.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] However, promises from the jQuery library were not Promises/A+ compatible until jQuery 3.0.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Node.js version 8 includes a utility that enables using the standard library callback-based methods as promises.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] The Future::AsyncAwait module was the subject of a Perl Foundation grant in September 2018.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Python 3.5 (2015) has added support for async/await as described in PEP 492 (written and implemented by Yury Selivanov).
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] On November 7, 2019, async/await was released on the stable version of Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Async functions in Rust desugar to plain functions that return values that implement the Future trait.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Currently they are implemented with a finite-state machine.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Swift 5.5 (2021) added support for async/await as described in SE-0296.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] The async/await pattern is especially attractive to language designers of languages that do not have or control their own runtime, as async/await can be implemented solely as a transformation to a state machine in the compiler.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Supporters claim that asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written with async/await that looks almost like traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] In particular, it has been argued that await is the best way of writing asynchronous code in message-passing programs; in particular, being close to blocking code, readability and the minimal amount of boilerplate code were cited as await benefits.
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Critics of async/await note that the pattern tends to cause surrounding code to be asynchronous too; and that its contagious nature splits languages' library ecosystems between synchronous and asynchronous libraries and APIs, an issue often referred to as "function coloring".
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Alternatives to async/await that do not suffer from this issue are called "colorless".
[src:poem-rust-web/async-await] Examples of colorless designs include Go's goroutines and Java's virtual threads.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] Poem is a full-featured and easy-to-use web framework with the Rust programming language.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] The `Endpoint` trait represents a type that can handle HTTP requests, and it returns a `Result<T: IntoResponse, Error>` type.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] The `handler` macro is used to convert a function into an endpoint.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] The extractor is used to extract something from the HTTP request.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] `Poem` provides some commonly used extractors for extracting something from HTTP requests.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] In the following example, the `index` function uses 3 extractors to extract the remote address, HTTP method and URI.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] By default, the extractor will return a `400 Bad Request` when an error occurs, but sometimes you may want to change this behavior, so you can handle the error yourself.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] In the following example, when the `Query` extractor fails, it will return a `500 Internal Server` response and the reason for the error.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] You can create custom extractors, see also `FromRequest`.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] All types that can be converted to HTTP response `Response` should implement `IntoResponse`.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] In the following example, the `string_response` and `status_response` functions return the `String` and `StatusCode` types, because `Poem` has implemented the `IntoResponse` trait for them.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] The `no_response` function does not return a value.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] We can think that its return type is `()`, and `Poem` also implements `IntoResponse` for `()`, which is always converted to `200 OK`.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] The `result_response` function returns a `Result` type, which means that an error may occur.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] The following example returns customized content when `NotFoundError` occurs.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] You can call the `with` method on the `Endpoint` to apply a middleware to an endpoint.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] It actually converts the original endpoint to a new endpoint.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] You can create your own middleware, see also `Middleware`.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] Commonly used as the type of extractor or response.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] A body object for requests and responses.
[src:poem-rust-web/latest-poem] Container that can be used to obtain path pattern from the request.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware often enables interoperability between applications that run on different operating systems, by supplying services so the application can exchange data in a standards-based way.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware sits "in the middle" between application software that may be working on different operating systems.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] It is similar to the middle layer of a three-tier single system architecture, except that it is stretched across multiple systems or applications.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Examples include EAI software, telecommunications software, transaction monitors, and messaging-and-queueing software.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] The distinction between operating system and middleware functionality is, to some extent, arbitrary.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] While core kernel functionality can only be provided by the operating system itself, some functionality previously provided by separately sold middleware is now integrated in operating systems.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] A typical example is the TCP/IP stack for telecommunications, nowadays included virtually in every operating system.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware is defined as software that provides a link between separate software applications.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] It is sometimes referred to as plumbing because it connects two applications and passes data between them.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware allows data contained in one database to be accessed through another.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] This makes it particularly useful for enterprise application integration and data integration tasks.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] It also facilitated distributed processing, the connection of multiple applications to create a larger application, usually over a network.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] when compared to the operating system and network services.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware offers some unique technological advantages for business and industry.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] For example, traditional database systems are usually deployed in closed environments where users access the system only via a restricted network or intranet (e.g., an enterprise’s internal network).
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] With the phenomenal growth of the World Wide Web, users can access virtually any database for which they have proper access rights from anywhere in the world.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware addresses the problem of varying levels of interoperability among different database structures.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware facilitates transparent access to legacy database management systems (DBMSs) or applications via a web server without regard to database-specific characteristics.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Businesses frequently use middleware applications to link information from departmental databases, such as payroll, sales, and accounting, or databases housed in multiple geographic locations.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] In the highly competitive healthcare community, laboratories make extensive use of middleware applications for data mining, laboratory information system (LIS) backup, and to combine systems during hospital mergers.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware helps bridge the gap between separate LISs in a newly formed healthcare network following a hospital buyout.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware can help software developers avoid having to write application programming interfaces (API) for every control program, by serving as an independent programming interface for their applications.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] For Future Internet network operation through traffic monitoring in multi-domain scenarios, using mediator tools (middleware) is a powerful help since they allow operators, searchers and service providers to supervise Quality of service and analyse eventual failures in telecommunication services.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Finally, e-commerce uses middleware to assist in handling rapid and secure transactions over many different types of computer environments.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] In short, middleware has become a critical element across a broad range of industries, thanks to its ability to bring together resources across dissimilar networks or computing platforms.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] In 2004 members of the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) carried out a study of Middleware with respect to system integration in broadcast environments.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] This involved system design engineering experts from 10 major European broadcasters working over a 12-month period to understand the effect of predominantly software-based products to media production and broadcasting system design techniques.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] The resulting reports Tech 3300 and Tech 3300s were published and are freely available from the EBU web site.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Message-oriented middleware (MOM) is middleware where transactions or event notifications are delivered between disparate systems or components by way of messages, often via an enterprise messaging system.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] With MOM, messages sent to the client are collected and stored until they are acted upon, while the client continues with other processing.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] software may queue, duplicate, translate and deliver messages to disparate systems or components in a messaging system.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Intelligent Middleware (IMW) provides real-time intelligence and event management through intelligent agents.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] The IMW manages the real-time processing of high volume sensor signals and turns these signals into intelligent and actionable business information.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] The actionable information is then delivered in end-user power dashboards to individual users or is pushed to systems within or outside the enterprise.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] It is able to support various heterogeneous types of hardware and software and provides an API for interfacing with external systems.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] It should have a highly scalable, distributed architecture which embeds intelligence throughout the network to transform raw data systematically into actionable and relevant knowledge.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] It can also be packaged with tools to view and manage operations and build advanced network applications most effectively.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Content-centric middleware offers a simple *provider-consumer* abstraction through which applications can issue requests for uniquely identified content, without worrying about where or how it is obtained.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Juno is one example, which allows applications to generate content requests associated with high-level delivery requirements.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] The middleware then adapts the underlying delivery to access the content from sources that are best suited to matching the requirements.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] This is therefore similar to Publish/subscribe middleware, as well as the Content-centric networking paradigm.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware enables a client to use services running on remote systems.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware, it is possible for applications to send objects and request services in an object-oriented system.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] is middleware between applications and database servers.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] integration interface that operates between embedded applications, the embedded operating system, and external applications.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliance is a generic term referring to any form of middleware that manages policy rules.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] They can mediate between data owners or producers, data aggregators, and data users.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Among heterogeneous institutional systems or networks they may be used to enforce, reconcile, and monitor agreed information management policies and laws across systems (or between jurisdictions) with divergent information policies or needs.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliances support policy-based information management processes by enabling rules-based processing, selective disclosure, and accountability and oversight.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] IBM, Red Hat, Oracle Corporation and Microsoft are some of the vendors that provide middleware software.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Vendors such as Axway, SAP, TIBCO, Informatica, Objective Interface Systems, Pervasive, ScaleOut Software and webMethods were specifically founded to provide more niche middleware solutions.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Groups such as the Apache Software Foundation, OpenSAF, the ObjectWeb Consortium (now OW2) and OASIS' AMQP encourage the development of open source middleware.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Microsoft .NET "Framework" architecture is essentially "Middleware" with typical middleware functions distributed between the various products, with most inter-computer interaction by industry standards, open APIs or RAND software licence.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] Solace provides middleware in purpose-built hardware for implementations that may experience scale.
[src:poem-rust-web/middleware-distributed-applications] StormMQ provides Message Oriented Middleware as a service.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] The **OpenAPI Specification** (**OAS**), previously known as the **Swagger Specification**, is a specification for a machine-readable interface definition language for describing, producing, consuming and visualizing web services.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] Originally developed to support the Swagger framework, it became a separate project in 2015, overseen by the OpenAPI Initiative, an open-source collaboration project of the Linux Foundation.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] An OpenAPI Description (OAD) represents a formal description of an API that tools can use to generate code, documentation, test cases, and more.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] Swagger development began in early 2010 by Tony Tam, who was working at online dictionary company Wordnik.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] In March 2015, SmartBear Software acquired the open-source Swagger API specification from Reverb Technologies, Wordnik's parent company.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] In November 2015, SmartBear announced that it was donating the Swagger specification to a new organization called the OpenAPI Initiative, under the sponsorship of the Linux Foundation.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] Other founding member companies included 3scale, Apigee, Capital One, Google, IBM, Intuit, Microsoft, PayPal, and Restlet.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] On 1 January 2016, the Swagger specification was renamed the OpenAPI Specification (OAS) and was moved to a new GitHub repository.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] Two somewhat similar technologies, MuleSoft's RESTful API Modeling Language (RAML) and Apiary's API Blueprint, had been developed around the same time as what was then still called the Swagger Specification.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] The producers of both formats later joined the OpenAPI Initiative: Apiary in 2016 and MuleSoft in 2017.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] In July 2017, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.0.0 of its specification.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] In February 2021, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.1.0.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] In September 2025, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.2.0 of the OAS.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] Notable features include structured tags, first-class streaming media type support, support for arbitrary HTTP methods, clearer example semantics for serializations, OAuth2 device flow and metadata enhancements, and clarified path templating and routing semantics.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] The OAS describes the format for OpenAPI Descriptions (OADs), which can be used by a variety of applications, libraries, and tools.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] Applications can use OADs to automatically generate documentation of methods, parameters and data models.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] This helps keep the documentation, client libraries and source code in sync.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] When an OAD is used to generate source code stubs for servers, the process is called scaffolding.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] The paradigm of agreeing on an API contract first and then programming business logic afterwards, in contrast to coding the program first and then writing a retrospective description of its behavior as the contract, is called contract-first development.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] Since the interface is determined before any code is written, downstream developers can mock the server behavior and start testing right away.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] In this sense, contract-first development is also a practice of shift-left testing.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Specification is language-agnostic.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] With OpenAPI's declarative resource specification, clients can understand and consume services without knowledge of server implementation or access to the server code.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Initiative sponsored APIStrat from 2017 to 2019, converting it into the API Specifications Confererence (ASC) from 2020 to 2022.
[src:poem-rust-web/openapi-specification] Starting in 2023, the initiative has instead sponsored OpenAPI tracks at multiple conferences throughout the year.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:poem-rust-web/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:poem-rust-web/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
